  "nursesNote": "The transtheoretical model describes behavior change in stages, and the nurse matches support to the patient's current stage. In precontemplation the patient is not yet considering change, so the nurse raises awareness gently without pushing. In contemplation the patient is ambivalent and weighing it, so the nurse explores pros and cons. In preparation the patient is getting ready and planning, so the nurse helps set realistic goals and a plan. In action the patient is actively changing, so the nurse provides support and reinforcement. In maintenance the patient is sustaining the change, so the nurse focuses on preventing relapse. Relapse can occur and is treated as a normal part of change, not a failure: the patient is encouraged to resume without shame. The key principle is to meet the patient where they are and not force action before they are ready.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Assess the patient's current stage of change",
    "Match the intervention to the stage",
    "Avoid pushing action before the patient is ready",
    "Support and reinforce the action stage",
    "Treat relapse as normal and help the patient resume"
  ],
